data.content:
Three breaking changes hit your code. Here's each one and the fix:

---

### 1. `ExecuteUpdateAsync` — now takes `Func<>`, not `Expression<Func<>>`

Your manual expression tree won't compile. Replace the entire block with:

```csharp
await context.Blogs.ExecuteUpdateAsync(s =>
{
    s.SetProperty(b => b.Views, 8);
    if (nameChanged)
    {
        s.SetProperty(b => b.Name, "foo");
    }
});
```

No more `Expression.Lambda`, `Expression.Call`, etc. The parameter is now a regular lambda, so conditionals work naturally.

---

### 2. Complex type columns — names are now auto-uniquified

**Two changes:**

**(a) Sibling complex types** with same property names get a numeric suffix to avoid silent column sharing. If `ShippingAddress.Street` and `BillingAddress.Street` previously shared one `Street` column, EF 10 generates `Street` and `Street1`. To preserve old behavior, pin names explicitly:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Customer>(b =>
{
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.ShippingAddress, p =>
        p.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("Street"));
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.BillingAddress, p =>
        p.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("Street"));
});
```

**(b) Nested complex types** now use the full path. `Order.Payment.BillingAddress.City` was column `BillingAddress_City`, now becomes `Payment_BillingAddress_City`. To keep the old name:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Order>()
    .ComplexProperty(o => o.Payment)
    .ComplexProperty(p => p.BillingAddress)
    .Property(a => a.City)
    .HasColumnName("BillingAddress_City");
```

> **If you have existing migrations/data**, you'll need to either pin `HasColumnName` to the old names or generate a new migration that renames the columns.

---

### 3. `IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger` — new `logCommandText` parameter

Every method (`CommandReaderExecuting`, `CommandReaderExecuted`, `CommandScalarExecuting`, etc.) gained a `string logCommandText` parameter. Add it:

```csharp
public class MyLogger : IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger
{
    public InterceptionResult<DbDataReader> CommandReaderExecuting(
        IRelationalConnection connection,
        DbCommand command,
        DbContext context,
        Guid commandId,
        Guid connectionId,
        DateTimeOffset startTime,
        string logCommandText)       // ← new parameter
    {
        // Use logCommandText for logging (has redacted constants)
        // Use command.CommandText for the actual executed SQL
    }
}
```

`logCommandText` contains SQL with inlined constants redacted (unless `EnableSensitiveDataLogging` is on). Use it for logs; use `command.CommandText` for execution logic.
